insert  into `t_event_dtls`(`Id`,`Event_Name`,`Event_Type`,`Event_Description`,`Event_Details`,`Posted_Date`,`Total_View`,`Total_View_Today`,`New_Status`) values (7,' BHUTAN OBSERVED WORLD SOIL DAY 2019 ','Festival','                  Bhutan observed the World Soil Day (WSD) 2019 at Khamdang Lower Secondary School (KDLSS), Khamdang gewog under Trashi Yangtse Dzongkhag on 5th December 2019 \n                ','<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">Bhutan observed the World Soil Day (WSD) 2019 at Khamdang Lower Secondary School (KDLSS), Khamdang gewog under Trashi Yangtse Dzongkhag on 5<span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; font-size: 0.7em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">th</span>&nbsp;December 2019. More than 900 participants from eights gewogs of Trashi Yangtse Dzongkhag including teachers and students of KDLSS witnessed the event, which was graced by Trashi Yangtse Dzongdag, Dasho Thuji Tshering as the chief guest. Other invited guests included Trashi Yangtse Dratshang Lam Neten, Superintendent of Police, Dzongkhag Tshogdu Thrizin, Dasho Dzongrab, sector heads, Gewog Thrizins, Chiwog Tshogpas and representatives from Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation (BTFEC), Farm Machinery Corporation Limited (FMCL), Dzongkhag Hospital, and different agencies under the Department of Agriculture based in the region.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">The main objectives of observing the WSD are:</p><ol style=\"margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 25px; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; list-style-position: initial; list-style-image: initial;\"><li style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">To take time to thank the soil and all that it provides.</li><li style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">To salute our farmers and the landowners who are doing their part to protect and improve soil health.</li><li style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">To educate people and raise their awareness of the importance of soils and its sustainable management for food security, poverty reduction, climate change, sustainable development and essential eco-system functions.</li><li style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">To urge individuals, agencies, policy makers and government to recognize the problem of soil degradation and make an investment in sustainable soil management for national food security and sustainable future.</li></ol><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"><a href=\"http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSCN0083-1.jpg\" class=\"fancybox\" data-fancybox=\"gallery\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-2283\" src=\"http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSCN0083-1-300x158.jpg\" alt=\"DSCN0083 (1)\" width=\"300\" height=\"158\" style=\"vertical-align: baseline; margin: 0px 1.4em 0.4em 0px; padding: 0px; outline: 0px; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; float: left; max-width: 100%;\"></a><span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">The day reminded the gathering that soils are foundation of agriculture and eco-system services. About 95% of our foods come from the soil. Whether one is a farmer, a public servant, or a businessman in the city, everyone needs to remember that without soil, we will not be able to survive. Our very existence depends on the soil! However, what we fail to recognize is that soils are non-renewable resources in the human lifetime. We cannot replace the soils that we lose through soil erosion caused by water, tillage and unsustainable agriculture practices. It can take up to 1000 years to form 2-3 cm of soil. Therefore, soil conservation is essential to ensure food security and sustainable agriculture. For soil to feed us, we need to feed them and take good care. Soils are also essential to provide clean water, maintain underground and to adapt and mitigate climate change.</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">To mark the Day, a total of 19 stalls showcased various technologies and information related to soils and sustainable soil management by 11 agencies National Soil Services Centre (NSSC), National Organic Flagship Program, Dzongkhag Agriculture Office, National seed centre, Agriculture Machinery Centre, Farm Machinery Corporation Limited (FMCL), Dzongkhag Livestock Office, Karma Group of companies, Dzongkhag Hospital, Mountain Hazelnut Venture and ARDC Wengkhar. All these exhibitions were aimed at educating general public on the importance of soil and its sustainable management practices.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">In addition to exhibitions, quiz competition among eight gewogs and essay and art competition for the students were also held. Youth engagement in such event was felt critical as they can learn and gather information and also play critical role in spreading the message and information to the communities that they belong. In fact, the future of Bhutanese agriculture depends so much on our youths as the present farming population is ageing leaving behind uncertainty and great concern about the future farming of our great Nation.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">The WSD was officially adopted by the 68<span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; font-size: 0.7em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">th</span>&nbsp;session of the UN General Assembly held in December 2013 following the endorsement and request made by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the UN (FAO) Conference, in June 2013. The date of 5 December for WSD was chosen because it corresponds with the official birthday of H.M. King Bhumibol Adulyadej, the King of Thailand, who dedicated his entire life educating and helping his Thai farmers in promoting sustainable soil management practices.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">Finally, on the WSD, everyone present were urged to do their part in stopping the soil erosion and creating a safe and sustainable future noting that We have not inherited the Earth from our Ancestors, but only borrowed from our Future Children.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">The WSD2019 was organized jointly by the National Soil Services Centre of the Department of Agriculture, MoAF and the Trashi Yangtse Dzongkhag Administration with funding support from BTFEC, UNCCD, CARLEP and RGoB.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">- ontributed by WSD 2019 team, NSSC, DoA</p><table class=\"uk-table uk-table-striped\" style=\"background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); width: 1160px; max-width: 100%; margin-bottom: 15px;\"><tbody><tr style=\"background: none rgb(248, 249, 250);\"></tr></tbody></table>','2019-10-24',12,NULL,1),(8,'Message from Hon’ble Sanam Lyonpo on World Soil Day ','Others','                                                                                                                              Today, Bhutan joins the global community in observing the World Soil Day (WSD) – a global event to raise awareness of the importa','                                        <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify;line-height:150%\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">Today, Bhutan joins the global community in\nobserving the World Soil Day (WSD) – a global event to raise awareness of the\nimportance of soils and its sustainable management. The WSD was officially\nadopted by the 68th session of the UN General Assembly held in December 2013\nfollowing the endorsement and request submitted by the conference of the Food\nand Agriculture Organization of the UN, in June 2013. Soil is the foundation\nfor agriculture and ecosystem sustainability. It provides the basis for food,\nfeed, fibre and fuel production. In fact, 95% of our food comes from\nnature-soil. Without healthy soils, we will not be able to grow our food and\nachieve food security and eradicate hunger. Healthy soils are also essential to\nprovide clean water as it purifies the water that we drink. Other important\nroles played by soils include mitigation and adaptation to climate change and\nconservation of biodiversity. Healthy soils have the potential to store three\ntimes more organic carbon than the atmosphere and vegetation combined.\nLikewise, soils provide one of the largest reservoirs of biodiversity on earth.\nNotwithstanding the above facts, soil degradation through erosion is ever\nincreasing due to factors such as Hon’ble Minister Yeshey Penjor Ministry of\nAgriculture and Forests “ STOP SOIL EROSION, SAVE OUR FUTURE ” unsustainable\nagricultural practices, deforestation, and growing population pressures.\nClimate change impacts of extreme weather pattern, accelerated soil moisture\nevaporation and change in vegetation patterns will exacerbate soil degradation.\nGlobally, about 75 billion tons of fertile topsoil is lost each year. Without\naction now, by 2050 an estimated 1.5 million Km2 of land would be lost from\ncrop production. Given the rugged mountain terrain geographical condition, soil\nerosion caused by gravity flow, storm-water washing, landslides, flash-floods,\nwindstorm and tillage, thus are, number of threats to soil stability and\nfertility in Bhutan. Soil erosion can lead up to 50% loss in crop yield. It can\nalso lead to significant losses in soil biodiversity and its potential to\nmitigate and adapt to climate change. We are losing annually about 3 to 21 t\nha?1 of fertile topsoil due to soil erosion. This is a serious problem for\nmountain farming as the soils in mountain areas are generally poorly developed,\nshallow, and relatively infertile. The problem can become worst for the nation\nas more than 30% of the total agricultural land is situated on slopes as steep\nas 50% or more, which is considered unsuitable for cultivation by international\nstandards. Thus, the future soil degradation risk in Bhutan is extremely high\nand this calls for concerted efforts from all of us. Every one of us has a role\nto play. Farmers can adopt sustainable soil management practices such as terracing,\ncontour hedge rows, cover crops and limited tillage, while policy makers can\ninitiate and integrate sustainable soil management policies within the broader\nnatural resource management agenda and allocate resources. Likewise, researcher\nand extension personnel should innovate and reach out solutions and\ntechnologies to prevent and control soil erosion, while Kuensel Supplement\nIssued in the public interest by Thursday, December 5, 2019 National Soil\nServices Centre, Department of Agriculture, Ministry of Agriculture and Forests\ncivil society organizations can help raise awareness about the importance of\nsoils among the public especially youths. This year, I am happy that the WSD is\nbeing observed at Khamdang under Trashi Yangtse Dzongkhag, which is one of the\nremotest and fragile agriculture site in the country. I would like to\ncongratulate the National Soil Services Centre (NSSC) of the Department of\nAgriculture (DoA) and the Dzongkhag Administration, Trashi Yangtse for their\njoint collaboration in celebrating the global event in Khamdang. I also thank\nother agencies who are participating in the event as exhibitors to educate and\nraise awareness on the importance of our respective roles in sustaining the\nlong term productivity of our soils. Finally, as we celebrate the WSD, let me\nurge all the stakeholders to recognize soil erosion as a serious problem and\ntake necessary action to stop it for a safe and sustainable future. Without\ntimely action and investment in soil now, achieving food and nutrition security\nwould become an irreversible challenge. Together we can! Let’s join our hands\nand work together towards soil degradation neutrality. I wish everyone a\nSuccessful and Happy World Soil Day!</span><o:p></o:p></p>                                    ','2019-10-25',7,NULL,1),(9,'Visit of First Year (First Batch) ','Festival','                                                      etween 1616 AD and 1651 AD, Zhabdrung had to wage around five major against the major wars against the invading forces of Desi Tsangpa Phuntsho Namgyel and his successors. The Bhutanese militia under t','                                                            <h1 class=\"entry-title\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 0.1em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; line-height: 1.2em; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 24px;\">Visit of First Year (First Batch) Student of B.Sc. Organic Agriculture</span></h1><h1 class=\"entry-title\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0.1em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; line-height: 1.2em; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"><div class=\"entry_wrap fix\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><div class=\"entry_content\" style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 1.6em;\"><h3 style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-bottom: 1em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The first year (first batch) students of B.Sc. in Organic Agriculture of the College of Natural Resources, Lobeysa visited the Centre on 31</span><span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; font-size: 14px; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">st</span><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> October 2019. </span><span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-size: 14px;\">A new programme B. Sc. Organic Agriculture was launched at the College of Natural Resources, Royal University of Bhutan.<br></span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; font-size: 14px;\">The introduction of the B.Sc. Organic Agriculture programme is another mile stone in Bhutans journey towards achieving 100 % Organic Agriculture. </span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">With the main objective to develop human resource capacity in organic agriculture and to contribute to the countrys food security and sufficiency goals, the College of Natural Resources (CNR) in Lobesa, Punakha launched a BSc programme in Organic Agriculture on 29</span><span style=\"border-style: initial; border-color: initial; border-image: initial; outline-color: initial; outline-style: initial; font-size: 14px; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">th</span><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"> July 2019. A total of 35 (20 female and 15 male) students have enrolled in this course. </span></span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; font-size: 14px;\">It is a comprehensive four year programme integrating Crop and Livestock production</span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; font-size: 14px;\">.</span></h3><p style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-bottom: 1em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"><a href=\"http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/4J4A9027-1.jpg\" class=\"fancybox\" data-fancybox=\"gallery\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"></a></p></div></div></h1>                                                      ','2019-10-25',5,NULL,0),(11,'Sanam Lyonpo attends 14th session of UNCCD COP14','News','The UNCCD COP14, hosted by the Government of India, began from 2nd September and attended by about 8000 delegates including 93 Ministers from 196 countries;','                                                                                <div class=\"printfriendly pf-alignleft\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\">The UNCCD COP14, hosted by the Government of India, began from 2nd September and attended by about 8000 delegates including 93 Ministers from 196 countries; Intergovernmental organizations; Special and UN agencies; Civil Society organizations; and media personnel. The event was aimed at identifying mutually viable solutions to the growing challenges of desertification, land degradation, and drought. The UNCCD was adopted in Paris in 1994 to be a legally binding document for fighting desertification through sustainable land management and has been ratified by 196 countries and the EU.<br style=\"\">Bhutan became a member country of UNCCD in August 2003. As required by the Convention, Bhutan developed its National Action Program (NAP), the key instruments to implement the Convention, for combating land degradation in 2010 and realigned it to the UNCCD 10-year strategy (2008-2018) in 2014. Bhutan is also one of the 122 countries committed to set Land Degradation Neutrality (LDN) target.<br style=\"\">The Opening Ceremony of the High-Level Segment was inaugurated by H.E. Shri Narendra Modi, Prime Minister of India; The inaugural was also addressed by H.E. Dr. Ralph Gonsalves, Prime Minister of Saint Vincent &amp; the Grenadines; H.E. Mr. Prakash Javedkar, President of COP14 and Minister of Environment, Forest and Climate Change of India; H.E. Ms. Amina J. Mohammed, Dy Secretary General of the United Nations; and Mr. Ibrahim Thiaw, Executive Secretary of the UNCCD.<br style=\"\">During the ministerial round-table discussions and interactive dialogue sessions, Lyonpo Yeshey Penjor highlighted Bhutans commitment to ensuring sustainable management of our land resources and called upon all international partners to adequately support Bhutans efforts towards this goal. Lyonpo shared the profound words and wisdom of His Majesty The King of Bhutan, quoting that Land is not simply an economic issue in Bhutan it is an all pervasive issue affecting the very livelihoods and welfare of the people our very Gross National Happiness. Lyonpo reiterated Bhutans commitment to remain carbon neutral and the critical requirement to transition to a clean energy economy.<br style=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/b4a673bf8b99beef9c0f8b9241da601d.jpg\" class=\"fancybox\" data-fancybox=\"gallery\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"></a>On the sidelines, Lyonpo represented the Prime Minister of Bhutan at the event on The Mainstreaming of Organic Agriculture and Agroecology in the Himalaya Region. Policy Context in Bhutan, India and Nepal on Friday 6th September 2019. As the keynote speaker, Lyonpo delivered about Bhutans experience in Promoting Organic Agriculture and highlighted the successful organic agriculture initiatives in Bhutan which was notably well received by the audience.<br style=\"\">Lyonpo held bilateral meetings with his counterparts in the Government of India: Shri Prakash Javedkar, President of COP14 and Minister of Environment, Forest and Climate Change; and Shri Giriraj Singh, Minister of Animal Husbandry, Dairy &amp; Fisheries. They expressed satisfaction at the excellent state of bilateral ties of friendship and cooperation in all related sectors, which are marked by mutual understanding and goodwill, and enhanced by Prime Minister Modis recent visit to Bhutan. They reaffirmed their commitment to further strengthen cooperation in all areas of mutual interest in the related sectors, particularly in the area of livestock &amp; fisheries development, forests, etc.<br style=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.nssc.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/431cfcbad4ae90ef334616941577b1b6-1.jpg\" class=\"fancybox\" data-fancybox=\"gallery\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal;\"></a>The Peace Forest Initiative of the Korean Forest Services was launched during the High-level Segment of the UNCCD COP14, Delhi on 10th September. According to the Korean Forest Services, this initiative could ultimately contribute to the alleviation of political tension, reconciliation and can become a part of permanent peace building processes. COP14 provided an opportunity for relevant and like-minded stakeholders to discuss the future initiative as a way to deliver common sustainable sustainable development goals (SDGs).<br style=\"\">Mr. Jachyum Kim, Minister of Korea Forest Service of the Republic of Korea met with Lyonpo during the launch and expressed interest to learn more about Bhutans success story in its forests and environment conservation.<br></div>                                                                        ','2020-03-19',8,NULL,1),(13,'Organic Fertilizer demand for coming up cropping  ','Announcement','                                    NSSC is processing to procure and supply organic fertilizer for National Organic Flagship Program. As such, the Centre is in the process of compiling .....\n                 \n                ','                                                            <div class=\"entry_content\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; line-height: 1.6em;\"><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size